<!--msnavigation--><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><!--msnavigation--><td valign="top">
<table border="1" width="92%" bordercolor="#000086" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
  <tr>
    <td width="100%">
      <p align="center"><B><font face="Arial" size="2"><a href="../../index.htm">vesconite.com</a><font color="#FF0000">&nbsp;
      </font><font face="Arial" size="2" color="#000086">&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="techinfo_links.htm">Design
      technical information</a> &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      Imperial PV calculations&nbsp;</font></font></B></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<table border="0" width="89%">
  <tr>
    <td width="70%"><b><font face="Arial" color="#000086" size="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></b></td>
    <td width="30%"></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="70%"><B><font face="Arial" color="#000086" size="5">Imperial PV
      calculations</font></B></td>
    <td width="30%">
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in; text-decoration: none" align="right"><B><font face="Arial" color="#000086" size="3"><a href="metric_PV_calc.htm"> 			<U>Metric
calculations</U></a></font></B></P>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">All
plain bearing materials have limits in their ability to sustain a
given loading at a particular speed. This is known as the <b><font color="#000086"> pressure x
velocity </font></b> or <font color="#000086"><b> PV</b></font> limit. The heat buildup that limits the PV is
influenced by a number of factors including:</font>
</P>
<table border="0" width="102%">
  <tr>
    <td width="61%">
<ul>
  <li>
    <p STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Coefficient
	of friction between the bearing and the shaft</font></li>
  <li>
    <p STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Loading
	of surface, expressed as P</font></li>
  <li>
    <p STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Sliding
	speed, expressed as V</font></li>
  <li>
    <p STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Ability
	to dissipate the heat</font></li>
  <li>
    <p STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Lubrication
	and cooling available</font></li>
  <li>
    <p STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Dry,
	wet or immersed application</font></li>
</ul>
    </td>
    <td width="41%"><font face="Arial" size="3"><img border="0" src="images/PV.gif" align="right" width="255" height="180"></font></td>
  </tr>
</table>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Vesconite
and Vesconite Hilube are internally lubricated and have low friction
coefficients. These materials are also polymers, and as such cannot
dissipate the heat as easily as metals.<br>
The
following equations apply:<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></P>
<table border="0" width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0">
  <tr>
    <td width="19%" rowspan="2">
      <p align="left"><B><FONT color="#008000" face="Arial" size="3">Loading
(P) =</FONT></B></td>
    <td width="81%"><B><U><FONT color="#008000" face="Arial" size="3">mass supported per bearing (lbs)</FONT></U></B></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="81%">
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><B>
 <FONT color="#008000" face="Arial" size="3">
 shaft diameter (inches) x bearing length (inches)</FONT></B></P>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">The load <font color="#008000"><b>
(P)</b></font> is in Pounds per square inch (Psi)<br>
The
recommended design loading for general applications is 4000 Psi for
negligible sliding speeds.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;
</font></P>
<table border="0" width="86%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0">
  <tr>
    <td width="31%" rowspan="2">
      <p align="left"><B><FONT color="#008000" face="Arial" size="3">Surface
speed (V) =</FONT></B></td>
    <td width="69%" valign="baseline"><B><U><FONT color="#008000" face="Arial" size="3">RPM x 3.14 x shaft diameter (inches)</FONT></U></B></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="69%">
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in" align="left"><B>					<FONT color="#008000" face="Arial" size="3">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
12</FONT></B></P>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Surface
speed <b><font color="#008000"> (V) </font></b> is given as feet per minute.<br>
If there
is negligible or no load, the surface speed is limited to 1000 fpm in
unlubricated conditions. Higher surface speeds are acceptable when
lubricated or immersed in water.</font></P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">PV is
the combination of the load (P) in Psi and the speed (V) in fpm.<br>
The
units of<font color="#000086"> <B>PV</B> </font> are therefore Psi.fpm<br>
The
level of lubrication that is required is determined by the<font color="#000086"> <B>PV</B></font>.
This lubrication is required to dissipate the heat build-up and to
reduce the friction coefficient.</font></P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in">&nbsp;
</P>
<div align="center">
  <center>
<TABLE width=582 BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 bordercolor="#FFCCCC" bgcolor="#FFECEC">
	<COL WIDTH=55*>
	<COL WIDTH=201*>
	<TR VALIGN=TOP>
		<TD WIDTH=121>
			<P><B><font face="Arial" size="3" color="#000086">PV &lt; 2500</font></B></P>
		</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=455>
			<P STYLE="font-weight: medium"><font face="Arial" size="3">No
			lubrication is required although lubrication aids a long life.</font></P>
		</TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN=TOP>
		<TD WIDTH=121>
			<P><B><font face="Arial" size="3" color="#000086">PV &lt; 5000</font></B></P>
		</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=455>
			<P STYLE="font-weight: medium"><font face="Arial" size="3">Initial
			lubrication on installation of the bearing</font></P>
		</TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN=TOP>
		<TD WIDTH=121>
			<P><B><font face="Arial" size="3" color="#000086">PV &lt; 10 000</font></B></P>
		</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=455>
			<P STYLE="font-weight: medium"><font face="Arial" size="3">Regular
			lubrication is required</font></P>
		</TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN=TOP>
		<TD WIDTH=121>
			<P><B><font face="Arial" size="3" color="#000086">PV &lt; 20 000</font></B></P>
		</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=455>
			<P STYLE="font-weight: medium"><font face="Arial" size="3">Circulating
			oil lubrication is required</font></P>
		</TD>
	</TR>
	<TR VALIGN=TOP>
		<TD WIDTH=121>
			<P><B><font face="Arial" size="3" color="#000086">PV &gt; 100 000</font></B></P>
		</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=455>
			<P STYLE="font-weight: medium"><font face="Arial" size="3">Bearing
			must be immersed in water</font></P>
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>
  </center>
</div>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="3">Vesconite
can be easily lubricated by grease, oil, water and certain fluids.<br>
Where
the application has a PV higher than 10 Mpa.m/min, please contact
VescoPlastics.<br>
While
many applications do not require lubrication, lubrication is useful
as it promotes extra-long life. Even once off initial lubrication at
installation gives a better wear life. Simple <FONT COLOR="#0047ff"><a href="bearing_groove.htm">grooves</a></FONT>
further enhance life substantially.</font></P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom: 0in"><font face="Arial" size="1">Updated&nbsp; Jan 25 2002</font></P>
